Ford Kenya leader and NASA principal Moses Wetang&rsquo;ula yesterday was cleared by the IEBC to run for reelection.He said he will leave his Senate campaigns to MPs allied to his party as he concentrate on national politics.&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need to conduct any campaigns here to retain the seat. I will concentrate on campaigning for NASA throughout the country to ensure we send the corrupt Jubilee regime home,&rdquo; Wetang&rsquo;ula said.This comes after his competitor holding the ODM ticket, Bonny Nyongesa, said he will take on Wetang&rsquo;ula, not as NASA leader, but as a competitor.&ldquo;Let him brace for a uphill task. This is going to be the mother of all battles. I&rsquo;m sure I will trounce him,&rdquo; he said.Nyongesa was cleared to run by the IEBC just before Wetang&rsquo;ula.He said he will offer alternative leadership. He spoke in Bungoma.Wetang&rsquo;ula, who was accompanied by Wiper leader Kalonzo Musyoka and a host of NASA-leaning politicians, warned the IEBC they will not accept any rigging.&ldquo;The IEBC should ensure a free and fair process, failing which the country will land in trouble,&rdquo; he saidWetang&rsquo;ula also warned police against being used by Jubilee to intimidate opponents. He claimed Interior CS Joseph Nkaissery is being used by NCIC&rsquo;s Francis ole Kaparo to block fair comments.&ldquo;We want to warn Kaparo that his role is not to deprive us out fundamental right of freedom of speech,&rdquo; Wetang&rsquo;ula said.He will face Jubilee&rsquo;s Juma Mukhwana, ANC&rsquo;s David Makali and Nyongesa.brace for a tough battleMeanwhile, Makali has said he is ready to face Wetang&rsquo;ula on the ballot. He said he has put all strategies and mechanisms in place and has the ability to clinch the seat.Makali spoke on Sunday in Bungoma town after handing in his papers and being cleared by the IEBC to participate in the race. He contested the seat in 2014, during the Bungoma Senate by-election and came a distance third after Wetang&rsquo;ula and former Webuye MP Musikari Kombo.Makali said the youth, the elderly, women and all the boda boda operators in all nine constituencies in the county have promised to support him.&ldquo;I call upon my competitors to uphold peace and to carry out peaceful campaigns by desisting from spreading hate messages and inciting the youth,&rdquo; he said. The IEBC will determine whether this election will be credible, he said, adding politicians should give them time.